 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uriggorsmortus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>RiggorsMortus</A> at: 6/28/02 8:10:17 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udeezle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Deezle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Noble Squire</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(6/28/02 7:32:05 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fpaladinsofnorrathgeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15920.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sylvergryphonbrotherhood.com/members/thumbs/thumb_deezle.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Spell Difficulties...</span><hr size=1> Kaldolur...here's a few notes about stunning.<br>
<br>
Interrupting spell casters is one of our biggest jobs in the high end game. It's important at lower levels too, but it becomes more so when to get 50+. With Cease, Desist, and Stun, you can be a top notch spell interrupter and royal pain in the butt to all caster NPC's, hehe.<br>
<br>
Whenever you get into a fight with a spell casting NPC, pull out the shield and one hander so you can bash (unless you're soloing and your one hander does a lot less damage than your 2 hander...even then it's kind of a judgement call. Until I got my Fiery Avenger I had a Wurmy and shield for my 1hs / shield set up and an Arbitor's Combine Greatsword for my 2 hander, and after a while I gave up bashing with the shield and pulling out the Wurmy when I was soloing because it did so much less damage than the ACGS and I could still interrupt most spells with stuns and the mob died much quicker with the ACGS).<br>
<br>
You should have 3 stuns memmed for spell interruption; Cease, Desist, and Stun. Make a hot button called STUN and set it up like this:<br>
<br>
/cast 1<br>
/cast 2<br>
/cast 3<br>
<br>
This is assuming your stuns are memmed in the first 3 available slots in the top of the bank of spells. If not just substitute the appropriate spell slot numbers, but for now lets assume they're in the first 3 slots.<br>
<br>
Put Cease in the first slot, always. It's one of the fastest casting (1.5 seconds) and the lowest mana cost (15) stuns. In the other 2 slots put Desist and Stun; placement of these is a bit more debatable as you need to decide whether saving mana is more important to you (Desist is only 25 mana but Stun is 60) or having a better chance to get the spell off in time is more important (Desist has a casting time of 1.8 seconds but Stun is only 1.5). I personally have Cease, then Stun, then Desist, as with most of the mobs I'm fighting interrupting every spell is much more important and mana cost isn't such a big deal.<br>
<br>
The beauty of this hot button is that it will always attempt to cast Cease first. If you have already used this button in a fight and Cease is still grayed out it will move to the next stun and attempt to cast that. If that stun has also been used in the last few seconds and is unavailable, it will move to the 3rd stun and attmept to cast that. Using this method you should always have at least one stun available at any given time. Also you can hover your mouse over one button, and as you soon as you see the &quot;target begins to cast a spell&quot; message you can very quickly click to interrupt.<br>
<br>
Interrupting spells is all about shaving off tenths of a second so you can get that bash or stun off before the mob completes its spell. So, general idea is to try to bash first to instantly interrupt, then cast a stun if the bash misses. You can either do this as 2 separate actions, or combine the bash into your STUN hot button to do it all at once:<br>
<br>
/doability (whichever number slot your bash button is in in your bank of combat buttons on the right side of your screen)<br>
/cast 1<br>
/cast 2<br>
/cast 3<br>
<br>
The good part about this button is that by hovering your mouse over this button in a fight and hitting it as soon as you see the spell casting message, you're interrupting spells in the absolute fastest (and therefore most successful) way. The negative aspect to this is that you're casting a stun every time without checking to see if your bash interrupted the spell and made the stun unneccesary, and thereby wasting mana. However, if you do it this way you can hit hit D twice and your autoattack button again to resume fighting. This will make you duck, then stop ducking, then start attacking again because when you ducked it turned autoattack off.<br>
<br>
I prefer to keep bash and stun as 2 separate buttons, that way I don't have to interrupt my own stuns when a bash hits, but some paladins like them all as one button, it depends on your style of play.<br>
<br>
A word of warning...when you start chain stunning, the mobs will REALLY dislike you and go right after you. This is why paladins (along with sk's, for other reasons) have a reputation for being very good at aggro management, they can pull a mob off a caster faster than anybody else, with the possible exception of SK's, by making the mob hate them more than the caster. This is good news if you're main tank in your group, not oso good if you're not. This is also the reason why I don't have my stun button set up to include bashes, as I don't want to accidentally stun when I don't need to and draw excess aggro if I'm not the MT.<br>
<br>
Also, repling to your earlier comment about stopping attacking while casting spells: not true. The timer that counts off in between your sword swings is NOT reset when you cast spells. So, to maximize your potential as a spells casting melee, try to cast spells JUST AFTER a sword swing. If the casting time of the spell is less than the delay of your weapon (adjusted for any haste items or spells you might have on you), you will have no loss of speed in your attack. Stunning to gain aggro is a typical thing to use this method for. However, this strategy goes out the window when you're stunning to interrupt spells of course, then you just want to get the stun off as fast as possible. <p>Deezle Suture - 
